    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly. Critics argue that substantive due process can hinder the legislative process, as unelected judges have the power to strike down laws based on their personal views of fairness, potentially over-riding the democratic process. This can create unpredictability, as judges may be perceived as creating new rights or extending existing ones beyond what was envisioned by the framers of the Constitution. For instance, in cases like Griswold v. Connecticut, which established a right to privacy related to contraception, critics argue this is judicial overreach, not an established constitutional guarantee, hence meddling with the law-making process. Such criticism, however, often clashes with the view that these judicial interpretations are necessary to protect minority rights from the tyranny of the majority, ensuring all citizens enjoy their fundamental rights irrespective of fluctuating public opinion.",
